on, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"about 1108–":"about 1108–Deceased","1108–Male":"1108–Deceased","1112–Female":"1112–Deceased","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","1086–Female":"1086–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","Abt 1130":"about 1130","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1108":"about 1108","1201":"1201","1112":"1112","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1108":"1108","Walton Deyville, Warwickshire, England":"Normandy, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Etouteville-, Sur-Mer, Seine-Inferieure, France":"Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Daiville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Darvill</b>, a habitational name someone from any of the places in France called Orville (Orne, Pas-de-Calais), Urville (Auche, Calvados, Manche), or Orival (Charente, Seine-Maritime, Somme), with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’.","French: habitational name for someone from either of two places called Arville, in Loir-et-Cher and Seine-et-Marne, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":107,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":116,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Daiville was born about 1108, in Normandy, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Deiville, was 24 and his mother, Mrs. Richard Deiville, was 23. He married de Stuteville about 1130, in Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"about 1108–":"umbes 1108–Surnud","1108–Male":"1108–Surnud","1112–Female":"1112–Surnud","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","1086–Female":"1086–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","Abt 1130":"umbes 1130","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1108":"umbes 1108","1201":"1201","1112":"1112","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1108":"1108","Walton Deyville, Warwickshire, England":"Normandy, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Etouteville-, Sur-Mer, Seine-Inferieure, France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1108–":"noin 1108–Kuollut","1108–Male":"1108–Kuollut","1112–Female":"1112–Kuollut","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1085–Male":"1085–Kuollut","1086–Female":"1086–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","Abt 1130":"noin 1130","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1108":"noin 1108","1201":"1201","1112":"1112","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1108":"1108","Walton Deyville, Warwickshire, England":"Normandy, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Etouteville-, Sur-Mer, Seine-Inferieure, France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Ranska","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1108–":"environ 1108–Décédé","1108–Male":"1108–Décédé","1112–Female":"1112–Décédée","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1085–Male":"1085–Décédé","1086–Female":"1086–Décédée","about 1150":"environ 1150","Abt 1130":"environ 1130","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1108":"environ 1108","1201":"1201","1112":"1112","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1108":"1108","Walton Deyville, Warwickshire, England":"Normandy, Surrey, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Etouteville-, Sur-Mer, Seine-Inferieure, France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","life